<div class="markdown"><h4>Data Science Applications to Astronomy</h4><h1>Week 8: Model Building III:</h1><h1>Regularization</h1></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Recall the model for general least squares linear regression <span class="tex">\(y = A \theta + \epsilon,\)</span> where:</p><ul><li><p>the vector of measurement values is <span class="tex">\(y_{\mathrm{obs}}\)</span>, </p></li><li><p>the <strong><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_matrix">design matrix</a></strong> is <span class="tex">\(A\)</span>,</p></li><li><p>the coefficients to be inferred are <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span>, </p></li><li><p>the measurement errors <span class="tex">\(\epsilon \sim \mathrm{Normal}(0,\Sigma)\)</span>, and</p></li><li><p>the covariance matrix for measurement errors is <span class="tex">\(\Sigma^{-1}\)</span>.</p></li></ul><p>We can find the maximum likelihood estimator (also known as the best-fit for general least squares) analytically via</p><p class="tex">$$\hat{\theta}_{MLE} = (A^{T} \Sigma^{-1}  A)^{-1} (A^{T} \Sigma^{-1} \ y_\mathrm{obs} ),$$</p><p>or via maximizing a loss function equal to the log likelihood plus a constant</p><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{loss}_{MLE}(\theta) = -\frac{1}{2}\left(y-A \theta\right)^T \Sigma^{-1} \left(y-A \theta\right) + \mathrm{const}.$$</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Penalized Regression</h2><ul><li><p>Start with standard loss function</p></li><li><p>Add a <strong>penalty term</strong> that penalizes coefficients when they do something we don't like.</p></li><li><p>Some very common forms of regularization:  </p><ul><li><p>L2 penalty: "Ridge regression"</p></li><li><p>L1 penalty: "Lasso"</p></li><li><p>Both L1 and L2 penalties: "Elastic Net"</p></li></ul></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>L2 Regularization</h2><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{loss}_{L2,\lambda}(\theta) = -\frac{1}{2}\left(y-A \theta\right)^T \Sigma^{-1} \left(y-A \theta\right) -\frac{\lambda}{2} \sum_i \theta_i^2  + \mathrm{const}$$</p></div>


<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>With some algebra, one can show that </p><p class="tex">$$\hat{\theta}_{L2} = (A^{T} \Sigma^{-1}  A + \lambda I)^{-1} (A^{T} \Sigma^{-1} \ y_\mathrm{obs} ),$$</p><p>i.e., there is still an analytic solution for any regularization coefficient <span class="tex">\(\lambda\)</span>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>L1 Regularization</h2><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{loss}_{L1,\lambda}(\theta) = -\frac{1}{2}\left(y-A \theta\right)^T \Sigma^{-1} \left(y-A \theta\right)
-\frac{\lambda}{2} \sum_i \left|\theta_i\right|  + \mathrm{const}$$</p></div>


<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>Note that here <span class="tex">\(\hat{\theta}_{L1,1} = 0\)</span>.   I.e., we can find fits that has less non-zero parameters!</p><p>However, if we had chosen a smaller value of <span class="tex">\(\lambda\)</span>, then <span class="tex">\(\hat{\theta}_{L1,1} \neq 0\)</span></p></div>


<img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64,"/>


<div class="markdown"><p>As we increase , we can find <span class="tex">\(\hat{\theta}_{L1}\)</span> that have fewer and fewer non-zero values.</p><p>Unfortunately, there is no analtyic solution for <span class="tex">\(\hat{\theta}_{L1}\)</span>.   Instead, there are itterative algorithms for estimating <span class="tex">\(\hat{\theta}_{L1}\)</span>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Bayesian Interpretation</h2><p>In a Bayesian setting, we would want to work with the posterior distribution for <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span>.   If we assume a uniform prior for <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span>, then the posterior distribution becomes  <span class="tex">\(\theta \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\hat{\theta}_{MLE}, \Sigma_{\theta_{MLE}}), $ where $\Sigma_{\theta_{MLE}} = (A^{T} \Sigma^{-1}  A)^{-1}\)</span>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Since </p><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{Posterior} \propto \mathrm{Prior} \times \mathrm{Likelihood},$$</p><p>we can take the log of both sides to get </p><p class="tex">$$\ln(\mathrm{Posterior}) = \ln(\mathrm{Prior}) + \ln(\mathrm{Likelihood}).$$</p><p>If we replace the uniform prior for <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span> with a Gaussian prior,  <span class="tex">\(\theta \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\theta_0, \Sigma_{pr})\)</span>, then the log posterior becomes</p><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{loss}_{MAP}(\theta) = -\frac{1}{2}\left(y-A \theta\right)^T \Sigma^{-1} \left(y-A \theta\right)
-\frac{1}{2}\left(\theta-\theta_0\right)^T \Sigma_{pr}^{-1} \left(\theta-\theta_0\right) + \mathrm{const}.$$</p><p>If we set <span class="tex">\(\theta_0 = 0\)</span> and <span class="tex">\(\Sigma_{pr}^{-1} = \lambda I\)</span>, then this reduces to </p><p class="tex">$$\mathrm{loss}_{MAP}(\theta) = -\frac{1}{2}\left(y-A \theta\right)^T \Sigma^{-1} \left(y-A \theta\right)
-\frac{\lambda}{2}\left|\theta\right|^2  + \mathrm{const}$$</p><p>Therefore, the best-fit value of <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span> with an L2 regularization term is equivalent to the mean of the posterior distribution for <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span> with a Gaussian prior with zero mean and using a scaled identity matrix for the prior for <span class="tex">\(\theta\)</span>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h4>Comparison of Regularization methods</h4><table><tbody><tr><th align="center">No Regularization</th><th align="center">L2</th><th align="center">L1</th></tr><tr><td align="center"><span class="tex">\(\ell(\theta)\)</span></td><td align="center"><span class="tex">\(\ell(\theta) + \lambda \sum_i \theta_i^2\)</span></td><td align="center"><span class="tex">\(\ell(\theta)  + \lambda \sum_i \left|(\theta_i)\right|\)</span></td></tr><tr><td align="center">Not sparse</td><td align="center">Not Sparse</td><td align="center">Sparse</td></tr><tr><td align="center">Unique solution</td><td align="center">Unique solution</td><td align="center">Not guaranties</td></tr><tr><td align="center">Closed form solution</td><td align="center">Closed form solution</td><td align="center">Itterative algorithm</td></tr><tr><td align="center">Sensitive to outliers</td><td align="center">Sensitive to outliers</td><td align="center">Robust to outliers</td></tr><tr><td align="center">Bayesian interpretation</td><td align="center">Bayesian interpretation</td><td align="center">NA</td></tr></tbody></table></div>


<div class="markdown"><h1>Example Application to Fitting a Spectrum</h1></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Function to be approximated</h2></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>f(x) =  x - exp(-(x^2)/0.0025);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    # Generate the (x, y) data
    Random.seed!(42)
    num_fit = 1000    # Number of points used to create full model
    max_order = 120   # Maximum polynomial order allowed
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin  
    # Compute function to be approximated on dense grid
    x_all = range(-0.5, stop=0.5, length=num_fit)
    y_all = f.(x_all) 
    # Create a sparse polynomial to be approximated
    A_all = poly_design_matrix(x_all, max_order)
    w_true = fit_L1(A_all, y_all, log=-1.0, tol=1e-8)
end;</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Generate Simulated Data</h2></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin   # Parameters for simulated observations
    num_obs = 50
    _obs = 0.05
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    regen_data
    x_obs = range(-0.5, stop=0.5, length=num_obs)
    A_obs = poly_design_matrix(x_obs, max_order)
    y_obs = A_obs * w_true
    y_obs += _obs .* randn(length(x_obs))
end;</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2>Perform Fitting</h2></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    A_train = poly_design_matrix(df_train.x,max_order);
    A_test = poly_design_matrix(df_test.x,max_order);
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin	
    w_no_reg_full = fit_no_reg(A_train, df_train.y)
    pred_no_reg_full = A_all * w_no_reg_full
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin	
    A_all_trunc = view(A_all,:,1:max_order_trunc)
    A_train_trunc = view(A_train,:,1:max_order_trunc)
    A_test_trunc = view(A_test,:,1:max_order_trunc)
    w_no_reg_trunc = fit_no_reg(A_train_trunc, df_train.y)
    pred_no_reg_trunc = A_all_trunc * w_no_reg_trunc
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    w_L2 = fit_L2(A_train_trunc, df_train.y; log=logL2)
    pred_L2 = A_all_trunc * w_L2
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    w_L1 = fit_L1(A_train_trunc, df_train.y; log=logL1)
    pred_L1 = A_all_trunc * w_L1
end;</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
    idx_w_L1_keep = abs.(w_L1) .&gt; 1e-6
    A_L1_refit_train = view(A_train_trunc,:,idx_w_L1_keep)
    w_L1_refit = fit_no_reg(A_L1_refit_train, df_train.y)
    A_L1_refit_test = view(A_test_trunc,:,idx_w_L1_keep)
    A_L1_all_refit_all = view(A_all_trunc,:,idx_w_L1_keep)
    pred_L1_refit = A_L1_all_refit_all * w_L1_refit 
end;</code></pre>
